7 Jul 2015 Liberia: Boy's death not due to Ebola, but dog-eating
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507071222.html?viewall=1
[The people of Nedoweh are now stating that the 17 year old young male, whose death was attributed to Ebola, did not die of the disease, but from eating a dead poisoned dog. The young male's corpse tested positive for the Ebola virus.

Regardless of the actual cause of death, the boy and at least 2 contacts tested positive for Ebola virus, indicating the virus is still circulating in Liberia. But it would be helpful to determine the origin of the virus that infected the 17 year old in order to better control spread of the virus. - Mod.LK]

8 Jul 2015 Liberia: Initial Ebola test on Liberia dog carcass negative: sources
http://in.reuters.com/article/2015/07/07/us-health-ebola-liberia-idINKCN0PH2B520150707?rpc=401
[According to a health official in Liberia who asked for anonymity since research is ongoing, "I learned today [8 Jul 2015] the result was negative, but we have to be careful because the remains are in bad condition, and the test is designed for humans." Humans, monkeys and pigs are known to be able to carry the Ebola virus, but there has never been proof that dogs can carry it, although a 2005 study showed that dogs in areas of Gabon affected by past Ebola outbreaks had antibodies against it, suggesting they might be survivors.

See discussion in 2 Jul 2015 Liberia: UPDATE 2-Liberia investigating animal link after Ebola re-emerges in ProMED mail post "Ebola update (85): WHO update, ECDC, WHO statement, susp. research 20150705.3487558." In addition, the possibility of sexual transmission must be considered. See ProMED Ebola virus disease - West Africa (218): Liberia clinics, semen trans., S. Leone 20141127.2995708. - Mod.LK]

8 Jul 2015 Liberia: "GOL capable of controlling latest Ebola outbreak" - President Sirleaf
http://allafrica.com/stories/201507081239.html?viewall=1
[President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf said Liberia has the capability to adequately control the latest Ebola outbreak, as demonstrated by the immediate response of the Incident Management System (IMS) to the situation when reported.]

6 Jul 2015 Netherlands: Ebola threat closes emergency room, 6 quarantined
http://www.nltimes.nl/2015/07/06/ebola-threat-closes-emergency-room-six-quarantined/
[The emergency room of the Bravis hospital in Roosendaal has been closed after a man with symptoms of the highly infectious Ebola virus was brought in on Sat [4 Jul 2015], the hospital announced on Sun [5 Jul 2015].

According to the hospital, the Ebola virus has not yet been confirmed in the man, but all measures were taken to be safe. The RIVM [National Institute for Public Health and the Environment] was called in, and the patient was isolated immediately. The emergency room was closed down and is being cleaned by a specialized cleaning company. Patients are being redirected to the emergency room in Bergen op Zoom while the one in Roosendaal is closed.

The man was transferred to Erasmus MC in Rotterdam with special transport. He did not have contact with other patients in the waiting room of the emergency room. He did, however, have contact with 5 employees of the hospital. They are being watched for any symptoms. According to the hospital, there is no risk of infection in the hospital.

The decision on when the emergency room can open again will be made on Monday morning [6 Jul 2015] in consultation with a microbiologist.]

8 Jul 2015 Nigeria: Port Health Service intensifies Ebola surveillance: official
http://www.news24.com.ng/National/News/Port-Health-Service-intensifies-Ebola-surveillance-official-20150708
[Due to the reported new case of Ebola virus in Liberia, the Port Health Services (PHS) says it has intensified surveillance activities at the Nnamdi Azikiwe International Airport, Abuja. ... All passengers coming into the country and those travelling out were often screened before being allowed to enter or leave the airport.]

