Non-governmental organizations
------------------------------
8 Jul 2015 World Health Organization: WHO "unprepared to deal with Ebola" - panel
http://www.3news.co.nz/world/who-unprepared-to-deal-with-ebola---panel-2015070808#ixzz3fF3IZo68
[According to a United Nation's-appointed panel's highly critical report, issued on Tuesday [7 Jun 2015], WHO "tends to adopt a reactive, rather than a proactive, approach to emergencies" and failed to act on the warnings of experienced staff on the ground. The report also found that when WHO did finally mobilize, Director-General Margaret Chan and senior staff failed to show the "independent and courageous decision-making" required to deal with governments of the affected countries. In addition, the report indicated that WHO also failed to engage with local communities early on or to communicate what could be done, for example, to reduce the infection risk from burials.

The original report, with a link to the WHO response:
http://www.who.int/csr/resources/publications/ebola/ebola-panel-report/en/

The audio recording of the 30-minute virtual press briefing by the panel's chair, Dame Barbara Stocking, can be heard at the following URL:
http://terrance.who.int/mediacentre/presser/WHO-RUSH_Ebola_ Interim_ Assessment_ Panel_ presserVPC_07JUL2015.mp3.]

[Comment on criticism of WHO's Ebola response
---------------------------------------------
Reports on the acknowledged failure of WHO's response to the Ebola epidemic in West Africa are beginning to emerge. But there is as yet no acknowledgement that WHO was not set up to include epidemic rapid response teams.

Importantly, on 12 May 2015, in document A68/26, WHO wrote: "A minimum balance of USD 100 million is proposed for the contingency fund, based on the recommendations of the Review Committee on the Functioning of the International Health Regulations (2005) in relation to Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 whose implementation was urged by the Health Assembly in resolution WHA64.1 in 2011."
http://apps.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA68/A68_26-en.pdf
I have not seen any report that this recommendation was adopted, and if so, that it will be funded or suffer from the same lack of support as the H1N1 flu recommendation.

Article 2 of WHO's Constitution reads: In order to achieve its objective, the functions of the Organization shall be:
...
(d) to furnish appropriate technical assistance and, in emergencies, necessary aid upon the request or acceptance of Governments;
...
(g) to stimulate and advance work to eradicate epidemic, endemic and other diseases...
http://www.who.int/governance/eb/who_constitution_en.pdf

WHO was never set up with staff to investigate epidemics, only to give expert advice on how to deal with them. On request from a country hit by an epidemic, WHO has always asked the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to parachute in and deal with it, which CDC has always done expeditiously. In the last 35 years, WHO working with CDC and other international partners has succeeded in eradicating smallpox worldwide, eliminating autochthonous measles from the Americas, beating polio back to only 8 countries, beating back schistosomiasis in Egypt and guineaworm to only 4 countries in Africa, and interrupting transmission of onchocerciasis (river blindness) in 10 West African countries, among other signal achievements.

In its response to the criticism, WHO says:
"WHO is already moving forward on some of the panel's recommendations including ... the contingency fund to ensure the necessary resources are available to mount an initial response."

WHO called for a USD 100 million contingency fund in the wake of the 2009 influenza A (H1N1) epidemic, but member states never provided the money. I cannot find any mention of a USD 100 million epidemic contingency fund in the 16 Jan 2015 document "Implementation of the International Health Regulations (2005) Report of the Review Committee on Second Extensions for Establishing National Public Health Capacities and on IHR implementation" http://apps.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/EB136/B136_22Add1-en.pdf. Is WHO now expected to drop most of its other programs to deal with the present and future Ebola epidemics?

The criticism is unfair: nobody except Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF), Western military bioweapons defense forces and task force "Scorpio" (see ref. below) had any idea how to deal with urbanized or nosocomial Ebola, and foreign military were not politically acceptable in the beginning.

[ref: Steffen R, Melling J, Woodall JP, Rollin PE, Lang RH, Luthy R, et al. Preparation for emergency relief after biological warfare. J Infect. 1997 Mar;34(2):127-32. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9138135]

--
John (Jack) Woodall, PhD
<woodall@promedmail.org>

PS - Neither is there a contingency plan on how to ramp up vaccine production to deal with widespread urban epidemics of yellow fever (YF) if the virus were to be imported into vector-infested tropical states of India or China, which would make W. African Ebola look insignificant. Urban YF is easily avoidable by strict urban vector control -- which would also eliminate urban dengue in many places -- and shutting down the black market in fake YF vaccination cards.

I was a staff member of CDC and WHO in overlapping periods from 1975-1994 and am co-founder and associate editor of ProMED. - Mod.JW]

Vaccines
--------
6 Jul 2015 Ghana: Public forum on Ebola vaccine trial opens in Ho today
http://www.dailyguideghana.com/public-forum-on-ebola-vaccine-trial-opens-in-ho-today/

8 Jul 2015 Ghana RFI: on 5 Jul 2015 ProMED posted Ebola update (85), which contains the following quote:
"The [Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences] notes that the Phase I trial of the GSK vaccine in Europe produced adverse results, particularly, prolonged bleeding in 10-15 per cent of the vaccinated population. This it says is a serious adverse development that calls for extreme caution in approving clinical trials, both Phase I and Phase II, in the country."
http://www.promedmail.org/direct.php?id=3487558
[ProMED-mail has learned from a reliable source that prolonged bleeding has not been reported anywhere the vaccine has been tested and would like to know the original source of this report. - Mod.JW]

7 Jul 2015 Ghana: Mothers flee from child immunization over Ebola vaccine trial fears
http://m.starrfmonline.com/1.5012492

8 Jul 2015 Ghana: More Ghanaians volunteer for Ebola trial
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/More-Ghanaians-volunteer-for-Ebola-trial-367294

8 Jul 2015 Ghana: Ebola vaccine components do not cause Ebola disease!
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/features/Ebola-Vaccine-Components-Do-Not-Cause-Ebola-Disease-367172
[Ghanaian scientists -- Prof Fred Binka, Prof Kwadwo Koram, Dr Kwaku Poku Asante and the investigating team from the University of Health and Allied Sciences (UHAS), the Noguchi Memorial Institute for Medical Research (NMIMR) and the Kintampo Health Research Institute (KHSI) -- have teamed up in a multi-country effort to develop an effective Ebola vaccine.

The Ghana Academy of Arts and Sciences (GAAS) recently issued a public statement raising a number of concerns about the Ghana Ebola vaccine trials [See 5 Jul 2015, Ghana: doubts over integrity of Ebola trials
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Doubts-over-integrity-of-Ebola-trials-366573 in ProMED-mail post Ebola update (85): WHO update, ECDC, WHO statement, susp. research 20150705.3487558.]

The Ghanaian scientists provided a factual response to each issue raised by GAAS, [including the issue of prolonged bleeding in 10-15 per cent of the population.] This was revealed to be "factually erroneous information put out by the Academy, as per the explanation of the Ghanaian scientists. What was actually reported was that the human cells that prevent bleeding were reduced briefly, and this was managed professionally, "'but there was NO bleeding!'" [See ProMED-mail post Ebola update (80): WHO update, susp, vaccine, research, funding 20150621.3453753.

Also see: http://graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/45732-ebola-vaccine-trial-safe-experts-assert.html for a discussion of a forum held to clarify the vaccine trial. The vaccine research experts also included officials from the Food and Drugs Authority (FDA), the Noguchi Memorial Institute for Medical Research (NMIMR), the Ethics Review Committee of the Ghana Health Service (GHS), and the Vice-Chancellor of the University of Health and Allied Sciences (UHAS). - Mod.LK]

6 Jul 2015 Uganda: Ugandans eager to participate in Ebola studies -- Scientists said the response from the Ugandan community was remarkable
https://www.the-newshub.com/science/why-ugandans-are-eager-to-participate-in-ebola-studies
[The Phase II trial vaccine trial will be carried out jointly by the US National Institutes for Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) and the Makerere University Walter Reed Project (MUWRP).]

